text: Identification of the kinanthraquinone biosynthetic gene cluster by expression of an atypical response regulator Risa Takao ,1,2 Katsuyuki Sakai Hiroyuki Osada ,4 and Shunji Takahashi 1Graduate School of Science and Engineering, Saitama University, Sakura-ku, Saitama-shi, Saitama, Japan; 2Natural Product Biosynthesis Research Unit, RIKEN Centre for Sustainable Resource Science, Wako, Saitama, Japan; 3Molecular Structure Characterization Unit, Technology Platform Division, RIKEN Center for Sustainable Resource Science, Wako, Saitama, Japan; and 4Chemical Biology Research Group, RIKEN Centre for Sustainable Resource Science, Wako, Saitama, Japan ∗Correspondence: Shunji Takahashi, shunjitaka@riken.jp Recent advances in genome sequencing have revealed a variety of secondary metabolite biosynthetic gene clusters in actinomycetes. Understanding the biosynthetic mechanism controlling secondary metabolite production is important for utilizing these gene clusters. In this study, we focused on the kinanthraquinone biosynthetic gene cluster, which has not been identified yet in Streptomyces sp. SN-593. Based on chemical structure, 5 type II polyketide synthase gene clusters were listed from the genome sequence of Streptomyces sp. SN-593. Among them, a candidate gene cluster was selected by comparing the gene organization with grincamycin, which is synthesized through an intermediate similar to kinanthraquinone. We initially utilized a BAC library for subcloning the kiq gene cluster, performed heterologous expression in Streptomyces lividans TK23, and identified the production of kinanthraquinone and kinanthraquinone B. We also found that heterologous expression of kiqA, which belongs to the DNA-binding response regulator OmpR family, dramatically enhanced the production of kinanthraquinones. The kinanthraquinone biosynthetic gene cluster. Keywords: biosynthetic gene cluster, heterologous expression, polyketide synthase, secondary metabolite, Streptomyces

Microorganisms such as actinomycetes and fungi are a treasure trove of biologically active natural products with a wide variety of structures. Many important clinically applied drugs have been found from natural products and their derivatives (Newman and Cragg 2012). Among the bioactive compounds isolated from mi- crobes, about half are produced by actinomycetes (Berdy 2005). Recently, the efficiency of obtaining novel natural products has decreased due to the reisolation of known compounds, which is one of the main obstacles in novel bioactive drug development. However, the advanced DNA sequencing technology has enabled sequencing of a number of microbial genomes. Especially, the genome sequencing of actinomycetes has revealed a variety of secondary metabolic biosynthetic gene cluster (Bentley et al. 2002; Ikeda et al. 2003; Ohnishi et al. 2008). Despite abundant ge- netic resources, only a limited number of gene clusters involved in metabolite production have been characterized from a single strain. Most biosynthetic gene clusters found in the genome se- quence are cryptic gene clusters, which are not expressed under normal culture conditions in the laboratory. Therefore, the de- velopment of strategies to utilize genetic resources as chemical resources is the most important issue in the postgenome era.

Streptomyces shows morphological differentiation during its life cycle. There is a close relationship between secondary metabolite production and morphological differentiation. Gen- erally, the production of secondary metabolites initiates in the transition phase between vegetative growth and the formation of aerial mycelium with sporulation (Chater 1989). In Strepto- myces, secondary metabolites are also produced in response to various stimuli. Secondary metabolite production is reported to be induced by autoregulators (Horinouchi and Beppu 1992) and chemical stimuli (Onaka et al. 2001; Kawai et al. 2007; Nodwell and Cuthbertson 2011; Panthee et al. 2020). Constitutive expres- sion of pathway-specific transcriptional regulators such as SARP (Stutzman-Engwall et al. 1992; Kerr, Peden and Sharp 1997; Arias, Fernandez-Moreno and Malpartida 1999; Panthee et al. 2011) and LuxR (Schrijver and Mot 1999; Laureti et al. 2011; Panthee et al. 2020) is an effective approach to obtain natural products with a high yield. Moreover, the heterologous gene expression of the entire biosynthetic gene cluster with optimum promoters or reg- ulators in optimized Streptomyces hosts has been reported for the production of natural products (Komatsu et al. 2013; Amagai et al. 2017; Hashimoto et al. 2018).

We have previously studied a secondary metabolite biosyn- thetic gene cluster in Streptomyces sp. SN-593, which pro- duces reveromycin A (Osada et al. 1991; Takahashi et al. 2011), furaquinocins (FQ) I and J (Panthee et al. 2011), and 6-dimethylallylindole-3-carbaldehyde. Among metabolites of Streptomyces sp. SN-593, we have not yet characterized the biosynthetic gene cluster for kinanthraquinone (1) (Figure 1) (Takagi et al. 2018) because its productivity was not enough to carry out gene disruption analysis. In this study, to iden- tify the biosynthetic gene cluster for 1, we performed heterol- ogous expression of the entire gene cluster in Streptomyces livi- dans TK23, and successfully produced 1 and a novel derivative. We also evaluated the role of the kiqA gene by gene disruption and heterologous expression. KiqA is a member of the DNA- binding response regulator OmpR family (Wietzorrek and Bibb 1997; Liu et al. 2013), which is associated with the type II polyke- tide synthase (PKS) gene cluster. Here, we report that kiqA gene expression dramatically enhanced the production of 1 and its derivative. Ampicillin, kanamycin, and chloramphenicol were purchased from Nacalai (Kyoto, Japan). General DNA manipulations in Escherichia coli were performed according to standard protocols (Green and Sambrook 2012). The alkaline method was followed for low-copy plasmid isolation (Kieser 1984). PCRs were performed using a T100 thermal cycler (Bio-Rad). PrimeStar® HS DNA polymerase (Takara Bio, Inc.) and KOD-FX (TOYOBO) were used for gene cloning and colony PCR, respectively. Gene cloning conditions for PrimeStar® HS were as follows: 98 °C, 10 s; 58-68 °C, 10 s; and 68 °C, 0.5-3.5 min for 26-31 cycles, followed by a final incubation at 68 °C for 3 min. Colony PCR conditions for KOD-FX were as follows: 94 °C, 2 min; 63 °C, 30 s; and 72 °C, 30 s for 35 cycles, followed by a final incu- bation at 72 °C for 2 min. The oligonucleotide primers were pur- chased from Eurofins Genomics (Tokyo, Japan). For cloning of 1 gene cluster and in-frame deletion of 1 genes, λ-red recombina- tion was employed (Datsenko and Wanner 2000). DNA-sequence analysis was performed using a BigDye terminator version 3.1 kit (Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CA, USA). All routine in silico DNA work was performed using the Geneious software package (Biomatters). Bacterial strains, plasmids, and culture medium

The bacterial strains and plasmids used in this study are listed in Table S1, and the PCR primers are listed in Table S2. E. coli DH5α and NEB10-β were used as the hosts for general cloning. E. coli strains were cultured in Luria–Bertani (LB) medium (Nacalai Tesque, Kyoto, Japan) at 28 or 37 °C. LB media were sup- plemented with the appropriate antibiotics (100 μg/mL ampi- cillin, 50 μg/mL kanamycin, 50 μg/mL apramycin, and 30 μg/mL chloramphenicol). Streptomyces sp. SN-593 was cultured in SK2 or reveromycin-producing medium (RM-PM) (Takahashi et al. 2011). S. lividans TK23 was prepared on M4YE agar plates and cultured in YEME media prior to protoplast preparation. R5 plates were used for protoplast transformation (Kieser et al. 2000). Unless otherwise stated, S. lividans TK23 transformants were precul- tured at 28 °C in SK2 medium with the appropriate antibiotics (5 μg/mL apramycin or 5 μg/mL thiostrepton) in 24(cid:5) test tubes (10 mL, 250 rpm) or K1 flasks (70 mL, 155 rpm). For metabo- lite analysis, the transformants were cultured in TSB medium (Becton, Dickinson and Company, USA). Vector construction for kiq gene cluster expression A BAC library of Streptomyces sp. SN-593 was constructed using a previously reported protocol (Komatsu et al. 2010, 2013). BAC clones containing the entire biosynthetic gene cluster for 1 were screened by PCR using 3 sets of primers (2885F/2885R, 2914F/2914R, and 2945F/2945R) (Table S2). Heterologous kiqA gene expression under the control of sav2794 promoter

Restriction enzyme sites were added to the kiqA gene by PCR amplification using the primer set (kiqA-NdeI-F/kiqA-Hind-R) (Table S2). The resulting PCR product was digested with NdeI and HindIII and ligated into pKU460::sav2794p-aac(3)I (Amagai et al. 2017) using T4 DNA ligase (HC) (Promega). After introduc- tion into E. coli DH5α, the resulting construct, pKU460::sav2794p- kiqA-aac(3)I, was confirmed by DNA sequencing. Then, the sav2794p::kiqA gene cassette was amplified using the primer set (EcoRI-2794p-F/kiqA-Hind-R). The PCR product was digested with EcoRI and HindIII and ligated into the integrative vector pTYM19 (Onaka et al. 2003) using T4 DNA ligase. After introduc- tion into E. coli DH5α, the expression vector, pTYM19::sav2794- kiqA, was obtained. Extraction and metabolite analysis by UPLC

An equal amount of acetone was added to 5 mL of culture medium, and sonication was performed for 15 s at 24 °C (TOMY UD-200). After centrifugation at 4000 × g for 10 min, the super- natant was concentrated. The water layer was extracted twice with 4 mL of ethyl acetate (EtOAc). The EtOAc layer was con- centrated and dissolved in 200 μL of methanol (MeOH). The ex- tracted sample was filtered through a Millex-LG syringe-driven filter unit (0.20 μm, 4 mm, Millipore). The filtrate was analyzed by Liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry (LC-MS) using an ACQUITY UPLC system equipped with an API-3200 mass spec- trometer. The UPLC system used an ACQUITY UPLC BEH C18 column (2.1 × 50 mm, 1.7 μm) with a flow rate of 0.5 mL/min. Solvent A consisted of 0.05% aqueous formic acid, and solvent B consisted of acetonitrile. After column equilibration with 5% solvent B, 1 μL of the extracted sample was injected into the col- umn, which was developed using a linear gradient of 5%-100% solvent B for 15 min, followed by maintenance at 100% solvent B for 20 min. Culture and isolation of the novel 1 derivative

S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2/pTYM19::sav2794p-kiqA was cultured in SK2 medium for 3 days. The culture broth was then inoculated into TSB medium (16 L) and cultured in a jar fermenter for 3 days at 28 °C and 150 rpm. Then, acetone (16 L) was added and filtered to remove the bacterial cells and the acetone extract was evaporated under reduced pressure. The remaining aqueous solution (16 L) was extracted twice with an equal volume of EtOAc. The organic layer was concentrated to dryness to obtain a crude extract (9.8 g). The extract was subjected to SiO2–MPLC with stepwise elution of a mixture of CHCl3–MeOH (100:0, 99:1, 98:2, 95:5, 90:10, 80:20, 50:50, and 0:100) to yield 24 fractions. The target fraction (CHCl3–MeOH 100:0) was detected by UPLC and concentrated in vacuo to remove the solvent. The dried material (1.4 g) was dissolved in a small amount of MeOH and applied for preparative HPLC with an isocratic solvent system of 50% CH3CN with 0.05% formic acid at a flow rate of 10 mL/min, and the peak from 27.5 to 29.5 min was collected to obtain 7 mg of kinanthraquinone B (5) as a yellow amorphous; UV λmax (MeOH) (log ε): 226 (4.30), 250 (4.26), 269 (4.32), 415 (3.89) nm (Figure S1); IR (ATR) νmax: 3390, 1664, 1628, 1576, 1485, 1423, 1365, 1323, 1250, 1068, 993, 777, 741 cm−1 (Figure S2). Feeding experiments for 5

S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV (vector control) was prepared on M4YE agar plates containing 5 μg/mL apramycin for 3 days at 28 °C. Three agar pieces were added to SK2 medium containing 5 μg/mL apramycin (24(cid:5) test tube) and cultured for 2 days. Three milliliters of the preculture (o.d.600 = 3) was added to 200 mL TSB medium, mixed well, and then divided into 24(cid:5) test tubes. Af- ter culturing for 2 days, 5 was added to a final concentration of 0.05 mm. The culture broths were collected every 24 h for an additional 3 days. Extraction and metabolite analysis were per- formed as described above. Search of the biosynthetic gene cluster for 1 Based on the structure of 1 (Figure 1), it was predicted to be biosynthesized by type II PKS. We thus focused on 5 type II PKS gene clusters found in the genome sequence of Strepto- myces sp. SN-593 (Panthee et al. 2020). To select a candidate gene cluster, we compared these with the grincamycin (2) gene cluster, which was speculated to produce biosynthetic intermediates (3, 4) similar to the structure of 1 (Figure 1) (Zhang et al. 2013). We selected a candidate gene cluster (27 ORFs) for 1 considering the similarity in gene organization and the presence of 2 O-methyltransferases (Figure 2). To obtain the full-length gene cluster, the BAC clone (pKU503_P21- E1) containing the target genes was selected by PCR screening. Cloning and heterologous expression of the kiq gene cluster in S. lividans TK23

To ensure sufficient genes for 1 biosynthesis, the kiq1 gene frag- ment (43 415 base) that contained orf (−4)–orf (−1) and orf (+1)–orf (+6) genes in the upstream and downstream of kiqA-S7 genes was cloned into pKU592aac(3)IV. To evaluate the core region responsible for 1 biosynthesis, the kiq2 gene fragment (kiqA-S7) (31 930 base), containing only homologous genes to the (Figure 2), was also cloned grincamycin gene cluster into and lividans TK23, pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2 were introduced into S. transfor- the respectively. The metabolite profiles mants (S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2) were analyzed by LC-MS. We found that the minimized kiq2 region was sufficient for the production of 1 and its derivative (Figure 3). Unexpectedly, 1 was detected as a minor product, whereas the novel derivative with the same absorption maximum as 1 (Figure S1) was the major product. In addition, we performed in-frame deletion of a ketoreduc- tase gene (kiqG) gene, which is generally involved in the early biosynthetic step of aromatic ring formation. The resulting construct, pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2(cid:6)kiqG, was introduced into S. lividans TK23, and the metabolite profiles of the transformants lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2(cid:6)kiqA) were analyzed (S. by UPLC. We found that all the transformants resulted in a nonproductive phenotype (Figure 3). The data also support that the kiq gene cluster is involved in the biosynthesis of 1 and its derivative. Finding of the derivative of 1 led us to analyze its chem- isolation and structure determina- ical structure. However, tion were still difficult due to a low yield in S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2. To maximize the productivity of 1 derivative, the utilization of a regulator gene was considered one of the most promising approaches. Therefore, we searched for a possible regulator that might enhance kiq gene expres- sion. Then, an antiSMASH search (Blin et al. 2019) (https:// antismash.secondarymetabolites.org/) was performed using the kiqA-kiqS7 sequence as the query (Figure 2) (the region from 2514 318 to 2546 247 nt of Streptomyces sp. SN-593 genome). The kiqA gene, which is presumed to be a member of the DNA-binding response regulator OmpR family, was found in the vicinity of type II PKS gene clusters (Table S5). First, to ex- amine the role of the kiqA gene for 1 biosynthesis, we con- structed an expression vector, in which only the kiqA gene was disrupted. The vector, pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2(cid:6)kiqA, was in- troduced into S. lividans TK23, and the metabolite profiles of the transformants (S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2(cid:6)kiqA) were analyzed. We then found that all of the transfor- mants showed a nonproductive phenotype (Figure 3), sug- gesting the function of KiqA as a positive regulator. expression on the production of 1 and its derivative. We con- structed a heterologous expression vector, pTYM19::sav2794p- kiqA, in which kiqA gene expression is regulated by the sav2794 promoter (Amagai et al. 2017). This expression vector was then introduced into S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2, and the metabolite profiles of the transformants (S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2/pTYM19::sav2794p-kiqA) were ana- lyzed by LC-MS. The results indicated that the productivity of 1 and its derivative was enhanced more than 10 times (Figure 3). Using this transformant, a large-scale culture was performed to isolate the 1 derivative and to determine its chemical structure. Structure elucidation of 5 Cultures of S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV::kiq2/pTYM19:: sav2794p-kiqA were extracted, fractionated by SiO2-MPLC, and purified by HPLC as described in the Materials and methods section. This yielded 5 as a yellow amorphous.

An anthraquinone skeleton was known to show a typical UV–Vis spectrum indicating maximum absorption at 226, 250, 269, and 415 nm (Figure S1). The IR spectrum showed char- acteristic absorption at 3390, 1664, and 1628 cm−1 (Figure S2), suggesting the presence of hydroxyl and carbonyl groups. The structure of 5 (Figure 4) was suggested to be similar to that of 1, when compared with the reported UV, NMR, and MS data (Takagi et al. 2018), 1 being originally isolated as a new an- thraquinone derivative from the culture broth of Streptomyces reveromyceticus SN-593-44. The UV–Vis spectrum and molecu- lar formula of 1 were reported 226, 247, 269, 305sh, and 420 nm and C21H19NO6, respectively (Takagi et al. 2018). The molecular formula of 5 was revealed as C21H18O7 by HRESIMS (Figure S3, found: m/z 383.1120 [M + H]+, calculated for C21H19O7 383.1125). The structure of 5 was suggested to have changed from the amide group of 1 to the carboxyl group. The 1H NMR data (Figure S4) indicated the existence of 4 aromatic methine protons at δH 8.06, 7.71, 7.61 and 7.55, an olefin signal at δH 6.48, 2 methoxy groups at δH 3.97 and 3.81, a methylene group at δH 3.10, and a singlet methyl group at δH 1.98. The 13C NMR (Figure S5) and HSQC (Figure S6) spectra indicated 21 carbons, which were clas- sified into 3 carbonyl signals at δC 187.5, 180.8, and 172.1, and 12 aromatic signals including 4 methine signals, which sup- ported the presence of a carboxyl group and an anthraquinone skeleton, 2 olefin signals, 2 methoxy signals at δC 60.5 and 56.5, a methylene signal at δC 38.6, and a methyl signal at δC 24.6.

The structure of 5 was mainly elucidated by NMR, in- cluding 2D NMR (Figure 5a and b). Cross peaks between H-3 (δH 7.71)/H-4 (δH 7.61) and H-7 (δH 7.55)/H-8 (δH 8.06) were ob- served in 1H–1H COSY (Figure S7). Two pairs of aromatic signals indicated the presence of 2 tetrasubstituted benzene rings in an anthraquinone skeleton. The anthraquinone skeleton was eluci- dated by 1H–13C HMBC correlations (Figures S8 and S9) from H-3 to C-1 (δC 159.1) and C-4a (δC 133.0), from H-4 to C-2 (δC 131.7), C-9a (δC 114.9), and a ketone at C-10 (δC 180.8), from H-7 to C-5 (δC 149.1) and C-8a (δC 125.9) and from H-8 to C-6 (δC 159.5), C-10a (δC 126.4), and a ketone at C-9 (δC 187.5). In this study, we isolated 1 and 5 by heterologous expression of the kiq gene cluster in S. lividans TK23. The speculated biosyn- thetic pathway is shown in Figure S11. Biosynthesis of 1 was initiated by the condensation of acetyl-CoA and 9 malonyl-CoAs by the polyketide synthase (minimal PKS) complex comprising ketosynthase, chain length factor, and acryl carrier protein containing a phosphopantetheinyl arm. The polyketide chain is folded into aromatic compounds by ketoreductase, aro- matase, and cyclase. Tailoring reactions include oxygenases, O-methyltransferases, and transamidase. Comparison of the chemical structure (Figure 1) and gene organization between the kiq and gcn gene clusters (Figure 2) suggested the presence of the kiqS1-S7 and kiqL genes, which show high homology to the gcnS1,2,3,4,5,7,8 and gcnG1-G3 genes involved in rhodinose biosynthesis and glycosylation, respectively (Tables S3 and S4). However, we could not isolate any compounds containing a sugar moiety in 1 and 5. LC/MS data indicating the presence of rhodinose glycosides were also not obtained. Based on the mode of glycosylation of grincamycin, it is speculated that glycosylation may be blocked by the presence of the methoxy group at C5 or C6. In addition, the presence of a hydroxyl group at the C2(cid:3) position (Figure 4) is essential as it provides a scaffold for subsequent glycosylation reactions. Several enzymes catalyzing transamidase reactions have been reported in secondary metabolite biosynthesis. For example, PhzH that catalyzes phenazine-1-carboxylic acid amidation to yield phenazine-1-carboxyamide was reported in Pseudomonas chlororaphis PCL1391 (Chin et al. 2001). FdmV that catalyzes fred- ericamycin C amidation to produce fredericamycin B was re- ported in Streptomyces griseus ATCC43944 (Chen et al. 2010). Based on the annotation of the kiq gene cluster (Table S3), we could not find the gene responsible for carboxyamide formation. There- fore, we speculated that an endogenous enzyme in S. lividans TK23 might catalyze the conversion of 5 to 1. To verify this possibility, we performed feeding experiments with 5 using S. lividans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV. Interestingly, the transformant of the vector control could convert 5 to 1 within 24 h of feed- ing (Figure S12). Although we do not rule out that an unchar- acterized enzyme in the kiq gene cluster might be involved in carboxyamide formation, the rapid conversion of 5 to 1 in S. livi- dans TK23/pKU592aac(3)IV suggested that 1 was mainly formed by an endogenous enzyme. Enhanced production of 1 and 5 by atypical response regulator KiqA Previously, based on the genome sequence, we found the FQ biosynthetic gene cluster in Streptomyces sp. SN-593. However, FQs were not detected in the culture extracts. Because activa- tion of the SARP family regulator is applicable for the enhanced production of secondary metabolites in Streptomyces, we focused on the constitutive expression of the regulator gene fur22, found in the FQ gene cluster. This approach led us to identify the novel compounds, FQ I and J (Panthee et al. 2011).

In the present study, we focused on KiqA of the DNA-binding response regulator OmpR family, which is located upstream of the kiq gene cluster. We succeeded in enhancing the pro- duction of 5 for structural determination by heterologous ex- pression of the kiqA gene. Based on a Pfam search, KiqA con- tains an N-terminal response regulator receiver domain and a C-terminal helix-turn-helix DNA binding domain. The hy- drophobic core of the OmpR DNA-binding fold has been re- ported to be conserved in the SARP sequences (Wietzorrek and Bibb 1997). An antiSMASH search using the kiq gene cluster showed that similar OmpR family response regulators are also present in other type II PKS gene clusters from Streptomyces (Table S5). KiqA shows 60% and 57% amino acid identity with atypical response regulators such as JadR1 (Yang et al. 2001) and Aur1P (Novakova et al. 2005), which have been reported as positive regulators of the jadomycin and auricin, biosyn- thetic gene clusters, respectively. Moreover, TetR type regula- tors, JadR2/JadR* and Aur1R, have been reported as negative regulators of the jadomycin and auricin gene clusters (Yang, Han and Vining 1995; Novakova et al. 2010; Zhang et al. 2013; Kormanec et al. 2014). On the contrary, the kiq gene cluster lacks a TetR negative regulator, suggesting that its mode of regula- tion is different from the gene clusters described above. More- over, feedback autoregulation by binding the end product have been reported for JadR1 (Wang et al. 2009) and Aur1P (Kutas et al. 2013). The existence of a similar regulatory mode by KiqA Bioscience, Biotechnology, and Biochemistry, 2021, Vol. 85, No. 3 through the binding of 1 and 5 will be investigated in future studies.

One of the 5 type II PKS gene clusters found in Streptomyces sp. SN-593 was cloned, heterologously expressed in S. lividans TK23, and identified for the production of 1 and its novel ana- log 5. Introduction of the kiqA gene, which belongs to the DNA- binding response regulator OmpR family, was found to dramat- ically enhance the production of 1 and 5. Because OmpR family regulators are found in type II PKS gene clusters, our approach might provide an insight for isolating novel natural products by genome mining.
